<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,602,833]" pageId="5" pageNumber="136">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,348,602,625]" pageId="5" pageNumber="136">Taxonomic notes</emphasis>
. The species was described from Tibet by Corti &amp; Draudt in the Seitz Supplementum (
<number box="[1372,1428,602,625]" pageId="5" pageNumber="136" value="1933.0">1933</number>
) combining with the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[441,591,637,660]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Anaplectoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="136" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[441,591,637,660]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="136">Anaplectoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Since then, its taxonomic position was debatable. The 
<typeStatus box="[1202,1295,637,660]" pageId="5" pageNumber="136">holotype</typeStatus>
of the taxon has not been found during our studies, but a male 
<typeStatus box="[733,825,672,695]" pageId="5" pageNumber="136">paratype</typeStatus>
and further two specimens are preserved in the Corti collection, 
<collectionCode box="[271,331,706,729]" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/8wbz-jkc3" name="Naturhistorishes Museum" pageId="5" pageNumber="136">NMB</collectionCode>
(one male and one female, the abdomen of the female is, unfortunately, missing). The specimens and their labels are illustrated in the figures 
<number box="[583,626,741,764]" pageId="5" pageNumber="136" value="5.0" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="4.0">4–6</number>
. The male genitalia of the species are illustrated here for the first time; the detailed comparison with its congener is given in the introduction and in the diagnoses of 
<taxonomicName box="[1130,1260,776,799]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Xestioplexia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="136" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albicollis">
<emphasis box="[1130,1260,776,799]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="136">X. albicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, therefore a full redescription of the species seems to be unnecessary.
</paragraph>
